The simile is taken from game hard pursued and flying into the thick wood where the hunter cannot easily fol· low; so the Epicureans recur to propositions that are unintelligible and hence hard to controvert. This is shown in the following chapter by two examples, which are foreign to the main subject; thatis taken up again inc. 26, 73·

52. 19. nihil fore ln nostra potestate. Inasmuch as the soul also consists of atoms, if the atoms had no power of varying from the course prescribed by the law of nature, all the activities of the mind must follow the law of nature, and free will would be excluded. For this reason Epi· curus conceded to the atoms a certain power of voluntary motion, which enabled him, he thought, to explain by the concurrence of the atoms thus varying from the perpendicular line both the origin of the universe and the freedom of the human will. Comp. Cic. De Fato, c. ro, ²²3 and especially Lucret. 11, 217 ff. and 251 ff.
